</span> <span class=\"bp\">ğ•œ</span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">]))</span> <span class=\"bp\">=</span> <span class=\"n\">span</span> <span class=\"bp\">ğ•œ</span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">]</span> <span class=\"o\">({</span><span class=\"n\">g</span><span class=\"o\">}</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">set</span> <span class=\"bp\">ğ•œ</span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">])</span> <span class=\"o\">:=</span> <span class=\"gr\">sorry</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>lean complains:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"n\">failed</span> <span class=\"n\">to</span> <span class=\"n\">synthesize</span> <span class=\"n\">type</span> <span class=\"kd\">class</span> <span class=\"kd\">instance</span> <span class=\"n\">for</span>\n<span class=\"bp\">ğ•œ</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"kt\">Type</span> <span class=\"n\">u_1</span><span class=\"o\">,</span>\n<span class=\"n\">_inst_1</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">field</span> <span class=\"bp\">ğ•œ</span><span class=\"o\">,</span>\n<span class=\"n\">g</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"bp\">ğ•œ</span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">],</span>\n<span class=\"n\">c</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"bp\">ğ•œ</span>\n<span class=\"bp\">âŠ¢</span> <span class=\"n\">has_scalar</span> <span class=\"bp\">ğ•œ</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">set</span> <span class=\"bp\">ğ•œ</span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">])</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>I am trying to see if I'm just reading the syntax wrong, so I want to chase down the <code>has_scalar</code> instance that is being used in the lemma above. I did some text searches like 'instance : has_scalar...' but I feel like there ha